32:55.822 --> 32:58.158
Besides, the teachers here...

32:58.325 --> 33:01.202
...aren´t that into student participation.

33:01.328 --> 33:03.330
They prefer to hear themselves talk.

33:03.330 --> 33:05.791
-What do you mean?
-You´lI see.

33:06.333 --> 33:10.253
This morning, we begin
our third required reading of the semester.

33:10.337 --> 33:12.839
The study of a novel
that offers everything...

33:12.839 --> 33:16.092
...and an author
who could have offered much more.

33:20.348 --> 33:24.351
That´s Robert Crawford. He´s been here
as long as most of the buildings.

33:24.351 --> 33:27.187
When William Forrester was 23, in 1953...

33:28.355 --> 33:31.066
...he set out to write his first book.

33:31.358 --> 33:35.529
Many aspiring authors talked about
writing the great 20th century novel.

33:36.864 --> 33:39.116
William Forrester did it...

33:39.366 --> 33:40.868
...on his first try.

33:40.868 --> 33:42.786
Have you read this?

33:43.370 --> 33:44.913
Yeah. You?

33:45.372 --> 33:47.374
Only about a dozen times.

33:47.374 --> 33:50.334
This was the only book
he chose to publish.

33:50.376 --> 33:53.839
For all we know,
it was the only one he chose to write.

33:55.382 --> 33:58.969
Your job over the next week
is to read it and tell me why.

33:59.386 --> 34:00.720
So...

34:01.888 --> 34:03.890
...will you be back tomorrow?

34:03.890 --> 34:06.893
Yeah. They want me to spend some time
on the court.

34:06.893 --> 34:08.353
I heard.

34:08.395 --> 34:11.648
Graduation was a little rough
on last year´s team.

34:12.399 --> 34:14.943
But it´s just like college, right?

34:15.402 --> 34:18.612
You get an education
and they get what they want.

34:18.905 --> 34:20.907
Maybe you both get what you want.

34:20.907 --> 34:22.284
Maybe.

34:24.411 --> 34:27.039
lt was very nice meeting you, Jamal.

34:27.414 --> 34:30.417
You, too, Claire.
Will you be around tomorrow?

34:30.417 --> 34:32.668
Not where you´ll be, but...

34:32.918 --> 34:35.338
...you might find me for lunch.

34:43.429 --> 34:46.683
-I didn´t say those two words yesterday.
-Why not?

34:47.434 --> 34:50.061
I want you to read more of my stuff.

34:53.940 --> 34:56.568
They talk a lot about you out there.

34:57.444 --> 34:59.446
All this legend bullshit.

34:59.446 --> 35:03.074
They got some stories.
People wonder if you killed someone.

35:03.950 --> 35:06.453
That, and wondering why
you been in here so long.

35:06.453 --> 35:10.123
I wouldn´t move. lt´s quiet.
You don´t hear nothing in here.

35:11.458 --> 35:13.877
Our place has noisy neighbours.

35:14.461 --> 35:17.464
Their kid is always yelling,
´cause he´s a year old...

35:17.464 --> 35:19.966
...or pops yells
´cause the kid is making noise.

35:19.966 --> 35:24.678
Then mom, on top of that, is yelling.
But it´s a different kind of yelling, ´cause...

35:25.472 --> 35:29.976
...the old man´s playing tunes for her and
she´s banging her head against the wall...

35:29.976 --> 35:32.103
...and she´s screaming--

35:32.479 --> 35:34.689
You better stir that soup.

35:35.481 --> 35:36.816
What?

35:37.984 --> 35:40.488
Stir the soup before it firms up.

35:47.493 --> 35:49.996
Why doesn´t ours get anything on it?

35:49.996 --> 35:51.790
Come on. Closer.

35:53.499 --> 35:54.500
Now.

35:54.500 --> 35:56.503
You got someone
doing that kind of yelling?

35:56.503 --> 35:59.422
What I have is an adult male. Quite pretty.

36:02.009 --> 36:04.427
Probably strayed from the park.

36:09.515 --> 36:11.559
A Connecticut warbler.

36:12.019 --> 36:14.729
You ever go outside to do any of this?

36:15.522 --> 36:18.525
You should have stayed
with the soup question.

36:18.525 --> 36:22.779
The object of a question is to obtain
information that matters only to us.

36:26.031 --> 36:29.244
You were wondering
why your soup doesn´t firm up?

36:29.536 --> 36:32.538
Probably because your mother
was brought up in a house...

36:32.538 --> 36:35.041
...that never wasted milk in soup.

36:35.041 --> 36:39.295
That question was a good one,
in contrast to, ´´Do I ever go outside?´´...

36:42.048 --> 36:46.595
...which fails to meet the criteria of
obtaining information that matters to you.

36:47.554 --> 36:51.057
All right. I guess I don´t have
any more soup questions.

36:52.559 --> 36:53.809
No?

36:54.059 --> 36:56.562
Why´d you say all that stuff
about me being black?

36:56.562 --> 36:59.440
lt had nothing to do with you being black.

36:59.566 --> 37:03.111
I wanted to find out
how much bullshit you´d put up with.

37:04.071 --> 37:06.072
-So you knew l´d come back?
-Yes.

37:06.072 --> 37:09.075
Just like I know
you´ll go to this new school.

37:09.075 --> 37:10.076
How do you know?

37:10.076 --> 37:14.748
Because there´s a question in your writing
about what you wish to do with your life.

37:15.582 --> 37:19.294
That is a question your present school
cannot answer for you.

37:24.090 --> 37:27.050
Let´s match up.
Wallace, you take Hartwell.

37:30.097 --> 37:32.099
What´s up? l´m Jamal.

37:32.598 --> 37:34.767
Just check it, all right?

37:37.604 --> 37:39.355
Check the ball.

37:39.605 --> 37:41.065
Come on.

37:44.109 --> 37:45.653
Ball´s in.

37:52.118 --> 37:53.870
Play him tough.

37:57.623 --> 37:59.417
Way to go, gang.

38:02.629 --> 38:04.756
D up. Let´s go, garbage.

38:05.131 --> 38:06.590
Come on.

38:07.133 --> 38:08.593
Step up.

38:14.139 --> 38:17.144
Why don´t you leave
the trash-talking back home?

38:17.144 --> 38:19.938
What? Get that goofy look off your face.

38:20.647 --> 38:23.148
-l´m gonna make you my son right now.
-Right.

38:23.148 --> 38:25.610
-You gonna be my son.
-Come on.

38:33.660 --> 38:35.161
Let´s go.

38:37.664 --> 38:39.665
-Come on, man.
-What?

38:39.665 --> 38:41.500
You´re too small.

38:47.673 --> 38:49.676
A little defence would be real nice.

38:49.676 --> 38:52.386
Coach, you´re right. A little defence.

38:53.679 --> 38:55.682
-Try to get past the line.
-What?

38:55.682 --> 38:57.891
I said, get past the line.

38:59.685 --> 39:01.187
Pressure.

39:03.690 --> 39:05.191
Too much.

39:09.695 --> 39:11.531
I need some help!

39:11.697 --> 39:14.324
Ten seconds. Let´s go the other way.

39:29.716 --> 39:31.216
-l´m taking your spot.
-What?

39:31.216 --> 39:33.218
-l´m taking your spot.
-You take nothing.

39:33.218 --> 39:34.678
Come on.

39:47.733 --> 39:49.902
My court, babe. My court.

39:55.741 --> 39:57.743
That´s how we play it down here.

39:57.743 --> 39:59.411
That´s right.

40:02.248 --> 40:05.250
John Hartwell´s just a rich kid
who wants as much of the spotlight...

40:05.250 --> 40:07.754
...as he can get in his senior year.
That´s all it is.

40:07.754 --> 40:11.674
-They take things real serious around here.
-lt´s a serious place.

40:13.259 --> 40:17.346
Serious enough that I end up here
getting lunch on my books most days.

40:18.264 --> 40:20.640
What´s that you´re working on?

40:21.266 --> 40:23.102
Forrester´s book.

40:23.269 --> 40:27.064
-You said you read it a dozen times.
-I know, but look at this.

40:27.273 --> 40:30.276
My dad got it for me. lt´s an early printing.

40:37.783 --> 40:40.286
-Listen, I got to go.
-But you just got here!

40:40.286 --> 40:44.123
I know, but, I forgot something.
I got to check up on something.

40:46.292 --> 40:48.209
l´lI see you later.

41:07.813 --> 41:09.566
´´Born: 1930...

41:10.315 --> 41:12.234
´´...in Scotland.´"

41:20.326 --> 41:23.745
´´Moved to New York
with his family in his late teens.

41:24.831 --> 41:27.916
´´Mr. Forrester was unavailable
for comment.´´

41:28.834 --> 41:30.753
Yeah, I bet he was.

41:30.795 --> 41:34.005
Are we now planning
to make these visits a habit?

41:35.841 --> 41:37.843
You said you knew l´d come back.

41:37.843 --> 41:40.388
Yes, but I thought you meant once.

41:40.846 --> 41:43.349
I need some help with a thing at school.

41:43.349 --> 41:45.726
Yes. This ´´thing´´ at school.

41:46.351 --> 41:49.354
And what ´´thing´´
are we talking about now?

41:54.860 --> 41:56.779
You ever read that?

42:01.366 --> 42:05.079
l´m trying. I just can´t seem to get past
the first 10 pages.

42:09.374 --> 42:11.084
As I recall...

42:12.377 --> 42:15.589
...it took awhile
to get past those pages myself.

42:18.383 --> 42:22.680
Christ, you´ve dog-eared one of them.
Show a little respect for the author.

42:29.394 --> 42:31.397
That´s you, isn´t it?

42:32.398 --> 42:34.274
You´re the author.

42:36.401 --> 42:40.029
I read the whole thing. lt´s not bad.
Especially the part--

42:41.906 --> 42:43.784
I know what it is.

42:43.910 --> 42:47.412
The last thing I need is another person
telling me what they think it is.

42:47.412 --> 42:48.914
I wasn´t going to say that.

42:48.914 --> 42:52.834
What were you going to say?
I should tell you everything about me?

42:52.918 --> 42:54.419
I told you about me.

42:54.419 --> 42:57.839
You could learn a little something
about holding back.

43:31.957 --> 43:35.044
If I ask you not to say anything
to anybody...

43:35.960 --> 43:37.921
...about here, us...

43:39.965 --> 43:42.759
...is that something I can trust you on?

43:47.472 --> 43:48.807
Yeah.

43:49.474 --> 43:51.018
I promise.

43:51.977 --> 43:53.311
Fine.

43:54.980 --> 43:58.316
And if I ask you to keep helping me
with my writing?

44:12.998 --> 44:15.624
There´ll be no questions about me...

44:16.000 --> 44:19.046
...my family,
or why there was only one book.

44:20.005 --> 44:21.840
Then I won´t ask.

44:23.008 --> 44:24.343
Good.

44:24.509 --> 44:26.260
And good night.

44:36.522 --> 44:38.481
What´s it feel like?

44:39.524 --> 44:40.525
What?

44:40.525 --> 44:43.069
Writing something the way you did.

44:44.529 --> 44:46.656
Perhaps you´ll find out.

45:03.549 --> 45:05.925
Listen, you 5-foot nothing....

45:08.053 --> 45:10.471
That´s what l´m saying, though.

45:13.558 --> 45:15.060
Kenzo, how old are you?

45:15.060 --> 45:16.352
Why?

45:16.560 --> 45:19.565
Look at your face!
Your mom didn´t do that to you?

45:19.565 --> 45:21.566
She started you young.

45:21.566 --> 45:24.861
Know where that comes from?
Eating too much cookie.

45:27.571 --> 45:29.323
Teresa told me.

45:29.574 --> 45:32.577
I like ´em big.
You got a problem with that?

45:32.577 --> 45:35.497
-Nothing wrong with a big girl!
-That big?

45:35.580 --> 45:40.001
lt don´t make a difference. lt´s like
when l´m with all three of your mothers.

45:40.084 --> 45:41.586
-Not my mother.
-Yeah.

45:41.586 --> 45:43.879
Hold on, Oscar Mayer wiener.

45:44.088 --> 45:48.718
Stop playing, man. You got beat like Tina
in school one day. I seen Duke smack you.

45:49.093 --> 45:53.140
Listen, throw it at your mama.
Every day, throw it towards your mama.

45:54.099 --> 45:56.601
Your mama. Stop throwing your mama.

45:56.601 --> 45:59.020
lt´s all in your tank, brother.

45:59.104 --> 46:00.604
Why you laughing?

46:00.604 --> 46:03.399
Man, your glasses are like Coke bottles.

46:05.611 --> 46:07.111
Classics.

46:08.613 --> 46:11.575
-You ever met somebody famous?
-How famous?

46:12.116 --> 46:14.369
Like, I don´t know, like...

46:15.620 --> 46:17.997
...somebody people would know.

46:18.122 --> 46:20.917
Nobody like that comes around here, man.

46:24.629 --> 46:26.840
Are you here for good now?

46:27.632 --> 46:30.301
Yeah. l´m just trying to get started.

46:34.138 --> 46:36.557
At least they look good, right?

46:48.653 --> 46:53.158
You´ll all be pleased to know this year´s
writing competition has been scheduled.

46:53.158 --> 46:56.161
For those choosing to take part,
all entries must be turned in...

46:56.161 --> 47:00.748
...before spring break, which means you
have a few months of procrastination left.

47:02.666 --> 47:06.128
Feel free to experiment
with a more proactive approach.

47:09.674 --> 47:11.301
Mr. Wallace?

47:11.676 --> 47:13.095
Please.

47:15.179 --> 47:19.141
I had a chance to review the files
sent over by your former school.

47:21.685 --> 47:23.688
Test scores, impressive.

47:23.688 --> 47:26.524
Actual classroom work, not so impressive.

47:28.193 --> 47:31.278
ls this the level of work
I should anticipate?

47:37.201 --> 47:39.161
Because, if it is...

47:40.205 --> 47:44.083
...it will help me determine
whether to treat you as a student...

47:44.208 --> 47:47.962
...or as someone who is here to pursue,
how should I put it...

47:48.712 --> 47:50.673
...other endeavours?

47:51.716 --> 47:55.553
Of course, your work will give you
ample opportunity to respond.

47:57.723 --> 47:59.765
Good day, Mr. Wallace.

48:05.729 --> 48:08.940
Just so you know,
you handled that the right way.

48:09.232 --> 48:10.860
How is that?

48:11.236 --> 48:14.822
You didn´t say anything.
The ones who do run into trouble.

48:15.740 --> 48:18.242
-John Coleridge.
-Jamal Wallace.

48:21.245 --> 48:23.747
So, how many people do say something?

48:23.747 --> 48:26.918
And actually stay in Crawford´s class?
Not many.

48:29.254 --> 48:31.338
I missed what you said.

48:32.256 --> 48:34.300
I didn´t say anything.

48:38.762 --> 48:40.681
You read all these?

48:40.764 --> 48:43.935
No, I just keep them
to impress all my visitors.

48:45.770 --> 48:47.647
All your visitors.

48:48.272 --> 48:50.775
We´ve been talking
about your book at school.

48:50.775 --> 48:55.445
People have been talking about it for years.
They just haven´t been saying anything.

48:56.280 --> 48:58.283
I think I got it down, though.

48:58.283 --> 49:01.786
I figure you were writing about
how life never works out.

49:01.786 --> 49:05.038
Really? You had to read a book
to figure that out?

49:06.790 --> 49:09.502
But Crawford´s messed up on it anyhow.

49:10.294 --> 49:13.298
He says the guy having trouble
after the war is really you.

49:13.298 --> 49:17.468
Some symbolism shit for all the problems
you were having with everybody.

49:18.302 --> 49:20.096
Robert Crawford?

49:20.304 --> 49:24.642
Yeah. I think it´s bullshit, though.
I think there really was somebody else.

49:32.317 --> 49:34.026
Mr. Johannsen?

49:34.318 --> 49:35.653
Here.

49:35.820 --> 49:39.281
Mr. Massie.
Another trip to your favourite destination.

49:40.324 --> 49:42.826
l´ve got four bags.
I can just leave them if you like.

49:42.826 --> 49:44.077
No.

49:46.831 --> 49:48.541
Come right in.

49:48.833 --> 49:50.834
How you doing, Mr. Johannsen?

49:50.834 --> 49:53.337
lt´s at least a haIf hour before the sun sets.

49:53.337 --> 49:57.049
Then you can begin
your panic-driven quest back to Manhattan.

49:58.342 --> 50:00.844
This should last you till next week.

50:00.844 --> 50:03.014
Your mail is in this one.

50:03.848 --> 50:05.349
Mr. Johannsen?

50:05.349 --> 50:07.851
-The essentials are in--
-Essentials?

50:07.851 --> 50:11.522
I took care of your bills.
I put all the copies in this one.

50:12.355 --> 50:15.860
The phone company wants to know
if you want to continue service...

50:15.860 --> 50:18.862
...seeing as you haven´t had a call
in about--

50:18.862 --> 50:22.575
I got your socks for the next few weeks.
They´re in this one.

50:23.366 --> 50:26.203
I have your latest check from accounting.

50:26.870 --> 50:31.124
They want to know if you cashed
the last one. lt´s showing up outstanding.

50:31.375 --> 50:33.920
Not as outstanding as it once was.

50:38.883 --> 50:41.885
l´m sorry.
I didn´t realise you had company.

50:41.885 --> 50:44.596
We were just having a discussion on...

50:45.388 --> 50:48.476
...German automobile history.
Care to join us?

50:49.393 --> 50:52.437
-No, l´m in the tow-away.
-Of course you are.

50:52.896 --> 50:54.398
See you next week?

50:54.398 --> 50:56.233
Not if l´m lucky.

51:01.905 --> 51:05.409
Why don´t you give that guy a break
and do your own shopping?

51:05.409 --> 51:07.412
Why are your socks inside out?

51:07.412 --> 51:08.912
Socks are badly designed.

51:08.912 --> 51:12.082
The seams are on the inside.
They hurt the toes.

51:13.416 --> 51:17.170
In some cultures, it´s good luck
to wear something inside out.

51:17.921 --> 51:19.423
You believe that?

51:19.423 --> 51:22.426
No. But it´s like praying.
What do you risk?

51:22.927 --> 51:26.763
And I do go outside. How do you think
those windows get cleaned?

51:29.932 --> 51:32.519
Now, about this professor of yours.

51:33.938 --> 51:37.357
How did it feel having him tell you
what you can´t do?

51:38.442 --> 51:40.444
Like he knew he was better than me.

51:40.444 --> 51:43.071
Then let´s show him what you can do.

51:44.448 --> 51:46.949
Why is it the words we write
for ourselves...

51:46.949 --> 51:51.038
...are always so much better
than the words we write for others? Move.

51:54.458 --> 51:55.751
Sit.

52:05.469 --> 52:06.971
Go ahead.

52:07.972 --> 52:09.472
Go ahead and what?

52:09.472 --> 52:10.849
Write.

52:12.976 --> 52:14.478
What are you doing?

52:14.478 --> 52:18.315
l´m writing. Like you´ll be,
when you start punching those keys.

52:24.989 --> 52:26.489
ls there a problem?

52:26.489 --> 52:28.533
No. l´m just thinking.

52:28.992 --> 52:31.369
No thinking. That comes later.

52:35.498 --> 52:37.834
You write your first draft...

52:38.502 --> 52:40.421
...with your heart.

52:40.504 --> 52:42.756
You rewrite with your head.

52:47.010 --> 52:49.387
The first key to writing is...

52:50.513 --> 52:52.141
...to write.

52:52.516 --> 52:54.184
Not to think.

53:04.528 --> 53:05.903
Jesus.

53:43.067 --> 53:45.735
ls there a chance you might sit down?

54:03.586 --> 54:06.714
´´A Season of Faith´s Pefection.´"
What´s this?

54:07.089 --> 54:08.966
Start typing that.

54:09.092 --> 54:13.263
Sometimes the simple rhythm of typing
gets us from page one to page two.

54:15.098 --> 54:18.643
When you begin to feel your own words,
start typing them.

54:41.625 --> 54:44.002
Punch the keys for God´s sake!

54:54.137 --> 54:55.430
Yes!

54:59.643 --> 55:01.770
You´re the man now, dog.

56:05.708 --> 56:07.085
Jamal?

56:07.710 --> 56:10.421
Whatever we write in this apartment...

56:11.213 --> 56:13.466
...stays in this apartment.

56:14.217 --> 56:15.927
No exceptions.

56:47.876 --> 56:50.086
Okay, let´s push it, guys.

56:56.384 --> 56:59.386
-That´s a foul.
-What do you mean? I had the spot.

56:59.386 --> 57:01.889
l´ll let you know when you got the spot.

57:01.889 --> 57:06.644
Gentlemen, our season begins in one week.
If I see this kind of thing one more time...

57:07.395 --> 57:10.564
...l´lI have you shooting fouls
to see who runs.

57:10.898 --> 57:12.817
ls that understood?

57:12.900 --> 57:14.193
One.

57:20.408 --> 57:21.700
Two.

57:25.413 --> 57:26.789
Three.

57:30.417 --> 57:31.836
Eleven.

57:35.924 --> 57:37.342
Twelve.

57:40.428 --> 57:41.929
Thirteen.

57:43.930 --> 57:45.557
Twenty-nine.

57:53.942 --> 57:55.567
Forty-eight.

57:58.946 --> 58:00.531
Forty-nine.

58:05.453 --> 58:06.912
Hold it.

58:08.956 --> 58:10.458
One more.

58:23.470 --> 58:27.058
That was one of the most
impressive things l´ve ever seen.

58:27.975 --> 58:30.978
Why do I know it wasn´t good enough
for either one of you?

58:30.978 --> 58:33.355
Shower up and get out of here.

58:35.983 --> 58:38.778
You may think we´re the same. We´re not.

58:46.493 --> 58:48.120
Mr. Wallace?

58:49.997 --> 58:51.624
Mr. Wallace.

58:51.999 --> 58:53.000
Professor.

58:53.000 --> 58:55.503
The latest paper you turned in...

58:57.504 --> 59:01.008
...displayed quite a bit of improvement
from your earlier work.

59:01.008 --> 59:02.884
-Thank you.
-Yes.

59:03.009 --> 59:05.012
How long did it take to write?

59:05.012 --> 59:06.513
I wrote it last night.

59:06.513 --> 59:08.098
Last night.

59:09.016 --> 59:11.936
Well, I have some things to finish up here.

59:12.019 --> 59:14.062
Good day, Mr. Wallace.

59:22.029 --> 59:24.032
That´s right. Select again.

59:24.032 --> 59:26.992
-´´Birds of a Feather´´ for $600.
-Answer..

59:27.034 --> 59:30.537
´´Vibrant in colour, its name borrows
from a Vivien Leigh character. ´´

59:30.537 --> 59:32.039
Scarlet tanager.

59:32.039 --> 59:34.542
No, it´s ´´What is the scarlet tanager?´"

59:34.542 --> 59:36.042
What is the scarlet tanager?

59:36.042 --> 59:38.546
See, you have to know the rules
to play the game.

59:38.546 --> 59:41.757
lt was written by a writer
you´ve never heard of.

59:42.549 --> 59:45.094
´´Thy duty, winged flame of spring

59:46.554 --> 59:48.680
´´is but to love and fly

59:49.056 --> 59:52.642
´´and sing´´ He was writing about
the song of the tanager.

59:53.560 --> 59:56.147
A song about new seasons, new life.

59:58.565 --> 01:00:00.567
That´s James Lowell, man.

01:00:00.567 --> 01:00:02.403
I know who he is.

01:00:03.070 --> 01:00:06.365
l´ll stay with ´´Poor Assumptions´"
for $800, Alex.

01:00:08.075 --> 01:00:10.578
Ever seen any scarlet tanagers
around here?

01:00:10.578 --> 01:00:13.372
They don´t stray that far from the park.

01:00:19.086 --> 01:00:22.923
So, your professor wasn´t exactly
full of praise this afternoon?

01:00:23.590 --> 01:00:25.218
Not exactly.

01:00:26.093 --> 01:00:29.597
There´s something you should know
about Robert Crawford.

01:00:31.598 --> 01:00:34.351
He wrote a book a few years after mine.

01:00:35.102 --> 01:00:38.813
All the publishers rejected it,
which was the right decision.

01:00:40.607 --> 01:00:43.110
lnstead of writing another one...

01:00:43.110 --> 01:00:46.197
...he took a job
teaching others how to write.

01:00:48.615 --> 01:00:50.117
How do you know all that?

01:00:50.117 --> 01:00:53.454
Just remember that bitterly
disappointed teachers...

01:00:54.120 --> 01:00:56.666
...can be either very effective...

01:00:57.625 --> 01:00:59.626
...or very dangerous.

01:01:46.673 --> 01:01:50.343
Okay, this is the first step tonight, guys.
Mailor on three.

01:01:51.678 --> 01:01:53.805
One, two, three, Mailor!

01:02:20.707 --> 01:02:22.334
Gold. Black.

01:02:25.211 --> 01:02:27.339
Straight and high, boys.

01:02:39.726 --> 01:02:40.727
What up, J?

01:02:40.727 --> 01:02:43.480
-You was in there tonight?
-26 points.

01:02:43.730 --> 01:02:46.733
8 out of 10 from the floor,
10 from 10 from the line.

01:02:46.733 --> 01:02:47.734
l´m supposed to miss that?

01:02:47.734 --> 01:02:49.236
lt was hot.

01:02:49.236 --> 01:02:52.238
You were putting some serious ink
on that stat page.

01:02:52.238 --> 01:02:54.032
What´s going on?

01:02:55.242 --> 01:02:58.619
Brothers are going to Red Rose.
I said we´d catch up.

01:02:58.745 --> 01:03:00.747
Friday night. Come on.

01:03:00.747 --> 01:03:03.625
Jamal, you plan on doing that every night?

01:03:04.251 --> 01:03:06.837
-Worked out, I guess.
-l´d say so.

01:03:09.255 --> 01:03:10.757
This is Fly.

01:03:10.757 --> 01:03:13.551
Hi. l´m Claire. You a friend of Jamal´s?

01:03:13.759 --> 01:03:15.553
Claire! Come on.

01:03:15.762 --> 01:03:17.348
l´m coming.

01:03:17.765 --> 01:03:21.184
Don´t hold up the bus too long.
Nice meeting you, Fly.

01:03:22.269 --> 01:03:24.937
What the hell you working there, man?

01:03:26.272 --> 01:03:27.941
Shut up, man.

01:03:29.276 --> 01:03:31.318
Yo, about Red Rose....

01:03:33.280 --> 01:03:36.783
I got to go to this dude´s house.
They do it every year.

01:03:37.283 --> 01:03:38.785
Don´t go off on this.

01:03:38.785 --> 01:03:42.205
You big time. Go on.
I don´t want to hold your bus up.

01:03:42.789 --> 01:03:44.791
Will you be around this weekend?

01:03:44.791 --> 01:03:47.626
Where do you think l´ll be? The Hamptons?

01:04:39.346 --> 01:04:42.848
Very nice talking with you.
Now, if you need anything...

01:04:42.848 --> 01:04:45.268
...please give me a call. Okay?

01:04:47.353 --> 01:04:48.687
Okay.

01:04:53.860 --> 01:04:56.696
Building up a collection of those things?

01:04:57.864 --> 01:04:59.490
Yeah, a few.

01:04:59.865 --> 01:05:02.285
Want to go outside for a while?

01:05:02.368 --> 01:05:04.579
Yeah. You know this place?

01:05:05.370 --> 01:05:07.749
I live in this place. Come on.

01:05:16.382 --> 01:05:20.219
They´ll be congratulating themselves
on your game till midnight.

01:05:20.887 --> 01:05:24.683
Which means l´lI have to cram tomorrow
for this test on Monday.

01:05:24.891 --> 01:05:26.393
Test on what?

01:05:26.393 --> 01:05:28.394
On the Sherlock Holmes books.

01:05:28.394 --> 01:05:31.397
They have us tracking down
all this worthless stuff like:

01:05:31.397 --> 01:05:33.857
Who introduced Watson to Holmes?

01:05:33.899 --> 01:05:37.570
They give it to you
´cause it forces you to read everything.

01:05:38.404 --> 01:05:40.824
Looks like it might be a while.

01:05:40.907 --> 01:05:42.409
Maybe so.

01:05:42.409 --> 01:05:45.912
So this friend, Fly,
how long have you known each other?

01:05:47.413 --> 01:05:50.416
A while. He was born there
and I was born there, too.

01:05:50.416 --> 01:05:52.334
-The Bronx?
-Yeah.

01:05:52.918 --> 01:05:54.421
Must be hard.

01:05:54.421 --> 01:05:55.755
What?

01:05:56.422 --> 01:05:58.508
New people, new school.

01:05:59.426 --> 01:06:00.926
lt´s not?

01:06:01.427 --> 01:06:02.678
No.

01:06:02.928 --> 01:06:07.349
What´s hard is growing up in a place
cops don´t even want to be in after dark.

01:06:08.434 --> 01:06:11.271
What´s hard is knowing you´re safe there.

01:06:11.438 --> 01:06:15.942
´Cause the people you need to worry about,
know you´ve got nothing to give them.

01:06:16.943 --> 01:06:19.445
So it´s a good thing you´re here.

01:06:21.447 --> 01:06:24.951
These people don´t think
I got anything to give them, either.

01:06:24.951 --> 01:06:28.413
Don´t let me get by you.
Once I get by you, l´ll score.

01:06:29.455 --> 01:06:32.333
Ready? Now stay in front of me, all right?

01:06:33.459 --> 01:06:35.002
All right?

01:06:37.963 --> 01:06:39.632
I got by you.

01:06:39.965 --> 01:06:42.093
You´re bigger than I am.

01:06:42.969 --> 01:06:44.971
lt doesn´t matter. You still got to defend.

01:06:44.971 --> 01:06:46.806
How do I do that?

01:06:47.473 --> 01:06:50.852
How do you play defence?
l´ll show you one way, here.

01:06:51.476 --> 01:06:53.103
Turn around.

01:06:57.483 --> 01:06:58.985
Feel that?

01:06:58.985 --> 01:07:00.486
I feel it.

01:07:00.486 --> 01:07:03.989
Now I know where you´ll go,
because I can feel you move.

01:07:04.990 --> 01:07:06.868
Try and move left.

01:07:08.994 --> 01:07:12.374
See, you can´t get around me.
I feel you moving left.

01:07:12.999 --> 01:07:14.834
Try and go right.

01:07:17.503 --> 01:07:19.004
l´m still here.

01:07:19.004 --> 01:07:22.508
I feel when you try to go right,
so you can´t go there, neither.

01:07:22.508 --> 01:07:24.551
Now try and get by me.

01:07:26.011 --> 01:07:27.472
Hold on.

01:07:28.515 --> 01:07:30.516
You have to dribble first.

01:07:30.516 --> 01:07:32.602
Dribble. Okay. Like....

01:07:34.520 --> 01:07:36.063
Like this?

01:07:39.024 --> 01:07:40.860
-Sorry.
-Claire.

01:07:42.027 --> 01:07:43.404
Daddy?

01:07:44.030 --> 01:07:46.449
Some of our guests are leaving.

01:07:47.032 --> 01:07:49.368
l´lI see you on Monday, okay?

01:08:02.048 --> 01:08:03.466
Claire?

01:08:04.550 --> 01:08:05.885
Yeah?

01:08:06.051 --> 01:08:07.845
lt was Stamford.

01:08:08.554 --> 01:08:10.055
Excuse me?

01:08:10.055 --> 01:08:11.556
At the bar in London.

01:08:11.556 --> 01:08:14.561
He was the one
who introduced Watson to Holmes.

01:08:14.561 --> 01:08:18.439
Might actually save you some time
after everyone´s done in there.

01:08:25.571 --> 01:08:28.073
You know how long
l´ve been working on that?

01:08:28.073 --> 01:08:32.828
lt ain´t one season of faith´s perfection.
Feels like I worked on it for two or three.

01:08:37.582 --> 01:08:40.836
You´re in that place
where you can´t even hear me.

01:08:41.086 --> 01:08:45.090
I could ask why you never left
this neighbourhood, and you wouldn´t--

01:08:45.090 --> 01:08:47.260
Paragraph three starts...

01:08:48.094 --> 01:08:50.513
...with a conjunction, ´´and.´"

01:08:51.095 --> 01:08:54.099
You should never start a sentence
with a conjunction.

01:08:54.099 --> 01:08:56.059
-Sure you can.
-No.

01:08:56.100 --> 01:08:57.603
lt´s a firm rule.

01:08:57.603 --> 01:08:58.854
No.

01:08:59.104 --> 01:09:03.568
lt was a firm rule. Sometimes using
a conjunction at the start of a sentence...

01:09:04.109 --> 01:09:08.113
...makes it stand out. And that may be
what the writer´s trying to do.

01:09:08.113 --> 01:09:10.116
And what is the risk?

01:09:10.615 --> 01:09:12.492
Doing it too much.

01:09:13.118 --> 01:09:16.621
lt´s a distraction
and could give your piece a run-on feeling.

01:09:16.621 --> 01:09:21.294
But the rule on using ´´and´´ or ´´but´´
at the start of a sentence is pretty shaky.

01:09:22.127 --> 01:09:25.130
Even though it´s still taught
by too many professors.

01:09:25.130 --> 01:09:29.341
Some of the best writers have ignored
that rule for years, including you.

01:09:32.639 --> 01:09:35.724
Well, you´ve taken something
which was mine...

01:09:37.643 --> 01:09:40.729
...and made it yours.
Quite an accomplishment.

01:09:43.649 --> 01:09:45.149
Thank you.

01:09:45.149 --> 01:09:47.652
The title´s still mine, isn´t it?

01:09:49.654 --> 01:09:51.115
I guess.

01:09:51.657 --> 01:09:54.744
lt was the neighbourhood that changed,
not me.

01:09:55.160 --> 01:09:56.661
I ain´t seen nothin´ changed.

01:09:56.661 --> 01:10:00.748
You ´´ain´t seen nothin´´´?
What in the hell kind of sentence is that?

01:10:02.667 --> 01:10:05.546
In here, don´t talk like you do out there.

01:10:05.671 --> 01:10:08.632
I was messin´ with you, man.
lt was a joke.

01:10:12.677 --> 01:10:17.099
Tell me about the neighbourhood back
when people were still reading your book.

01:10:17.682 --> 01:10:19.518
What did you say?

01:10:22.688 --> 01:10:23.688
Nothing.

01:10:23.688 --> 01:10:27.234
You said ´´back when people
were still reading my book.´´

01:10:29.194 --> 01:10:30.779
Didn´t you?

01:10:38.204 --> 01:10:40.163
We have 24 copies...

01:10:40.205 --> 01:10:42.958
...but l´m sorry, they are checked out.

01:10:46.210 --> 01:10:48.088
Thank you, anyway.

01:10:52.718 --> 01:10:54.219
Any luck?

01:10:56.222 --> 01:10:58.223
Did you get on the waiting list?

01:10:58.223 --> 01:11:00.434
Your book was checked out.

01:11:01.727 --> 01:11:03.227
And, yes...

01:11:03.227 --> 01:11:05.355
...I did pay for dinner.

01:11:05.730 --> 01:11:08.483
lt cost me $13, so you made your point.

01:11:10.235 --> 01:11:13.738
I tried to call to see what food you wanted,
but the phone kept ringing.

01:11:13.738 --> 01:11:16.241
I took the bell out 20 years ago.

01:11:22.248 --> 01:11:23.749
Let me ask you something.

01:11:23.749 --> 01:11:25.959
Why does a guy like you...

01:11:28.253 --> 01:11:31.256
...waste his time reading
National Enquirer?

01:11:31.256 --> 01:11:33.258
What´s wrong with it?

01:11:34.259 --> 01:11:35.260
lt´s trash, man.

01:11:35.260 --> 01:11:38.263
You should be reading
The Times or something.

01:11:38.263 --> 01:11:40.641
I read The Times for dinner...

01:11:42.267 --> 01:11:44.478
...but this is my dessert.

01:11:44.770 --> 01:11:47.563
They got some writing contest at school.

01:11:47.772 --> 01:11:50.275
-You ever enter one of those?
-A writing contest?

01:11:50.275 --> 01:11:51.985
-Yeah.
-Once.

01:11:52.777 --> 01:11:55.239
-A long time ago.
-Did you win?

01:11:56.281 --> 01:11:58.324
Well, of course I won.

01:11:58.783 --> 01:12:00.911
Like money or something?

01:12:01.787 --> 01:12:03.455
The Pulitzer.

01:12:06.791 --> 01:12:09.794
They make all the students
read in front of everyone.

01:12:09.794 --> 01:12:12.297
What the hell´s that got to do with writing?

01:12:12.297 --> 01:12:16.176
Writers write so that readers can read.
Let someone else read it.

01:12:16.801 --> 01:12:18.803
You ever read your own book?

01:12:18.803 --> 01:12:20.763
In public? Hell, no.

01:12:21.305 --> 01:12:23.599
I barely read it in private.

01:12:24.310 --> 01:12:28.021
You know those things they do,
that coffee shop reading shit?

01:12:28.814 --> 01:12:31.066
Do you know why they do it?

01:12:31.816 --> 01:12:33.318
To sell books, I guess.

01:12:33.318 --> 01:12:35.695
Because they want to get laid.

01:12:35.820 --> 01:12:38.823
Really? Women will sleep with you
if you write a book?

01:12:38.823 --> 01:12:41.952
They´ll sleep with you
if you write a bad book.

01:12:43.328 --> 01:12:45.914
-Did it ever happen to you?
-Sure.

01:12:48.833 --> 01:12:51.002
Did you ever get married?

01:12:52.837 --> 01:12:55.423
Not exactly a soup question, is it?

01:12:56.341 --> 01:12:58.135
No, I never did.

01:13:01.346 --> 01:13:03.849
But I learned a few things along the way...

01:13:03.849 --> 01:13:07.643
...which might help with this young lady
you always talk about.

01:13:09.354 --> 01:13:10.896
Like what?

01:13:13.358 --> 01:13:15.694
The key to a woman´s heart...

01:13:15.861 --> 01:13:18.988
...is an unexpected gift
at an unexpected time.

01:13:20.365 --> 01:13:22.867
You´re giving me advice on women?

01:13:22.867 --> 01:13:25.370
Unexpected gift, unexpected time.

01:13:28.373 --> 01:13:30.417
This is so unexpected.

01:13:34.379 --> 01:13:37.090
lt´s not a first printing or anything.

01:13:37.882 --> 01:13:39.383
Oh, my gosh.

01:13:39.383 --> 01:13:41.802
-What?
-This is a signed copy.

01:13:42.888 --> 01:13:45.890
I can´t accept this.
lt must have cost a fortune.

01:13:45.890 --> 01:13:48.393
lt didn´t cost that much, really.

01:13:48.894 --> 01:13:51.270
Maybe the bookstore missed it.

01:13:52.397 --> 01:13:55.232
Bookstores don´t usually miss this stuff.

01:13:56.400 --> 01:13:58.904
How´d you end up going to Mailor?

01:13:59.905 --> 01:14:02.866
Mailor was originally an all-boys´ school...

01:14:02.907 --> 01:14:06.494
...so, my father did
what anyone in his position would do.

01:14:07.912 --> 01:14:10.415
He got on the board and changed the rules.

01:14:10.415 --> 01:14:12.750
And every kid there knows it.

01:14:13.417 --> 01:14:14.920
They´d have done it anyway.

01:14:14.920 --> 01:14:18.673
That doesn´t change anything.
l´m still Dr. Spence´s daughter.

01:14:24.428 --> 01:14:27.223
That night at my home, after the game...

01:14:27.432 --> 01:14:30.727
...when you were showing me
how to play basketball:

01:14:32.938 --> 01:14:35.439
Was that all you were showing me?

01:14:37.442 --> 01:14:39.611
That´s not going to work.

01:14:39.943 --> 01:14:41.278
What?

01:14:41.946 --> 01:14:43.281
That.

01:14:43.447 --> 01:14:44.908
Why not?

01:14:47.452 --> 01:14:49.245
Ask your father.

01:14:49.955 --> 01:14:53.332
l´m not asking for some kind
of prenuptial agreement.

01:14:54.959 --> 01:14:56.960
lt´s just a question.

01:14:57.461 --> 01:15:00.757
Why must everything be
so black and white with you?

01:15:03.968 --> 01:15:05.970
I forgot the question.

01:15:05.970 --> 01:15:08.764
You don´t forget anything, Mr. Stamford.

01:15:23.488 --> 01:15:27.366
You don´t think he wrote it?
That´s a serious accusation, Robert.

01:15:27.992 --> 01:15:30.494
You come to the Faculty Board with this....

01:15:30.494 --> 01:15:32.914
l´m aware of how serious it is.

01:15:32.997 --> 01:15:35.000
lt´s remarkable work.

01:15:35.500 --> 01:15:37.001
You recognize any of it?

01:15:37.001 --> 01:15:39.087
lt smacks of something.

01:15:40.004 --> 01:15:41.839
But I don´t know.

01:15:42.506 --> 01:15:46.177
The boy does well in my class.
He had good scores coming in.

01:15:47.512 --> 01:15:49.514
Maybe he just needed direction.

01:15:49.514 --> 01:15:52.600
Carl, he´s a basketball player
from the Bronx.

01:15:53.017 --> 01:15:55.728
Who happens to have won 17 straight...

01:15:56.521 --> 01:15:59.106
...for a school that likes winning.

01:16:00.524 --> 01:16:03.653
Have you considered
he might just be that good?

01:16:09.034 --> 01:16:10.743
Not this good.

01:17:00.584 --> 01:17:03.629
Do you know
what the absolute best moment is?

01:17:04.588 --> 01:17:07.383
When you´ve finished your first draft...

01:17:08.092 --> 01:17:10.512
...and you read it by yourself.

01:17:11.595 --> 01:17:13.764
Before these arseholes...

01:17:14.098 --> 01:17:17.392
...take something
they couldn´t do in a lifetime...

01:17:18.101 --> 01:17:20.729
...and tear it down in a single day.

01:17:22.606 --> 01:17:24.859
People love that book, man.

01:17:25.109 --> 01:17:27.361
I didn´t write it for them.

01:17:28.612 --> 01:17:32.074
And when the critics
started all this bullshit about...

01:17:33.116 --> 01:17:36.078
...what it was I was really trying to say...

01:17:37.622 --> 01:17:39.832
...well, I decided then...

01:17:41.125 --> 01:17:43.211
...one book was enough.

01:17:44.628 --> 01:17:47.256
William, that was 50 years ago, man.

01:20:58.947 --> 01:21:02.159
I actually spent money on these tickets.
Come on.

01:21:02.451 --> 01:21:04.453
ls it still light outside?

01:21:04.453 --> 01:21:06.204
lt´s nighttime.

01:21:14.462 --> 01:21:15.798
Well?

01:21:16.965 --> 01:21:19.468
You look good. lt´s not the latest stuff--

01:21:19.468 --> 01:21:21.720
I wasn´t asking how I look.

01:21:21.970 --> 01:21:25.432
-I was asking, are we ready to go?
-Yeah. Come on, man.

01:21:27.475 --> 01:21:28.976
Let´s go.

01:21:34.483 --> 01:21:35.942
Come on.

01:21:46.494 --> 01:21:48.706
We play here in two weeks.

01:21:49.998 --> 01:21:53.335
I said, we play here in two weeks.
State tournament.

01:22:12.019 --> 01:22:14.480
Hold on. Let me get a programme.

01:22:49.558 --> 01:22:50.893
Damn.

01:24:06.133 --> 01:24:08.345
Let´s get you out of here.

01:24:10.138 --> 01:24:11.681
I got you.

01:24:40.669 --> 01:24:42.920
You used to get out, right?

01:24:43.671 --> 01:24:45.673
Yeah, a long time ago.

01:24:45.673 --> 01:24:47.675
-What happened?
-How should I know?

01:24:47.675 --> 01:24:50.135
I didn´t keep track of the time.

01:24:50.177 --> 01:24:52.638
Sorry for losing you back there.

01:24:52.680 --> 01:24:53.681
No apology needed.

01:24:53.681 --> 01:24:57.435
Good. l´ve got one more place.
lt´s quiet and on the way home.

01:25:03.900 --> 01:25:05.400
